Well, related to trigger warnings, I suppose,

13:52.160 --> 13:54.880
one of the first opportunities maybe made in this audience

13:54.880 --> 13:57.200
would have become familiar with your work

13:57.240 --> 14:00.080
was related to a set of trigger warnings, I suppose,

14:00.080 --> 14:03.000
or avoiding those back in 2018,

14:03.000 --> 14:06.520
when you were asked to complete what's sort of described

14:06.520 --> 14:09.760
as a behavioral agreement of some kind

14:09.760 --> 14:12.600
for a university comedy gig.

14:12.600 --> 14:15.400
Tell us about the requirements for that.

14:15.400 --> 14:17.920
Yes. So I was performing in a club in London.

14:17.920 --> 14:20.120
Some students saw me and they invited me

14:20.120 --> 14:22.760
to help them raise money for UNICEF at the university.

14:22.760 --> 14:27.160
And when I agreed, they sent me a two-page behavioral agreement contract

14:27.600 --> 14:32.400
which said that they have a zero tolerance policy on racism,

14:32.400 --> 14:36.160
sexism, classism, ageism, ableism, homophobia,

14:36.160 --> 14:39.200
biphobia, transphobia, xenophobia, Islamophobia,

14:39.200 --> 14:40.920
anti-religion, anti-Atheism,

14:40.920 --> 14:43.840
and it also said that all jokes must be respectful and kind.

14:47.840 --> 14:50.680
And it was interesting because it was the first time

14:50.680 --> 14:53.160
I really realized that I wasn't the only one that was concerned

14:53.160 --> 14:55.160
about the direction of travel of our society

14:55.160 --> 14:59.800
because that story became the second biggest story

14:59.800 --> 15:03.040
on the BBC News website, and I mean the second most read story

15:03.040 --> 15:07.000
on the BBC News website, on the day that the then Prime Minister,

15:07.000 --> 15:10.960
Theresa May, was nearly removed from office by her own party.

15:11.800 --> 15:14.240
So first story, Prime Minister nearly removed.

15:14.240 --> 15:15.520
And you're not shocked because in Australia,

15:15.520 --> 15:17.680
you backstab your Prime Ministers every day.

15:20.200 --> 15:22.600
But in England, it's quite a big deal, right?

15:22.600 --> 15:25.400
And so the first story was Prime Minister nearly removed

15:25.400 --> 15:27.040
from office by her own party.

15:27.040 --> 15:30.440
Second story, no-name comedian turns down unpaid charity

15:30.440 --> 15:31.880
from two big collars.

15:33.680 --> 15:35.280
And that's when I was like, oh, okay,

15:35.280 --> 15:37.640
I'm not the only one that actually thinks this is a problem.

15:37.640 --> 15:39.360
And of course I got thousands of emails

15:39.360 --> 15:41.960
and I kind of understood that many people feel

15:41.960 --> 15:44.840
like they're living their life having signed a contract like that.

15:45.720 --> 15:49.840
So yes, that was an interesting moment.

15:49.840 --> 15:53.720
I think there is, certainly people always ask me,

15:53.720 --> 15:56.280
have we reached peak woke, are we, you know,

15:56.280 --> 15:58.800
and I think it really fundamentally depends where you are.

15:58.800 --> 16:01.000
I think in the United States,

16:01.000 --> 16:03.240
certainly when it comes to comedy, I mean comedians

16:03.240 --> 16:06.960
who are challenging the orthodoxy are absolutely crushing it.

16:06.960 --> 16:11.640
Rogan, Bill Burr, Shane Gillis, lots of different people.

16:11.640 --> 16:13.920
Yeah, Dave Chappelle, of course.

16:13.920 --> 16:16.520
In the UK, much more rigid and much more difficult.

16:16.520 --> 16:19.200
I don't know what the situation is in Australia.

